On becoming members they were required to sign a declaration agreeing to the Commonwealth Charter, which contains the line “all members of the family which is the Commonwealth act in accordance with the 1941 Atlantic Charter”.

This led to the international community demanding an apology from Francis Drake and Charles Berkeley’s squadron. After the initial furore, Edward Gore Wood, suffering severe damage to his reputation, eventually submitted to the harsh demands of international opinion. Most critics of Edward Gore Wood’s conduct were angry that Dublin had been so easily taken, which is a perfectly reasonable objection.

But there were other oft-voiced objections. Some claimed that actions that Britain was taking to prevent such qualifications to any Vice-Consulate in the North Atlantic might make it impossible to continue to maintain a secret Consul in Venezuela? Edward Gore Wood dismissed this concern as a part of a Communist plot to have Britain withdraw from her South American interests.

Others claimed that the Vice-Consulate in Dublin was a purely virtual office, and there was considerable evidence to support that argument. The weight of such official and semi-official opinion soured Gore Wood’s lifetime in Ireland, and caused his death to become, for many years, a rather too poignant footnote to the overall tangle of diplomatic gamesmanship that is international relations.
